msgctxt "mn87:29.1"
msgid "“Acchariyaṃ, mallike, abbhutaṃ, mallike."
msgstr ""

# I find the PTS reading with the repeated pannaya to be implausible.
#. VAR: ativijjha maññe → ativijjha paññāya (pts1) | paṭivijjha paññāya (mr)
msgctxt "mn87:29.2"
msgid "Yāvañca so bhagavā paññāya ativijjha maññe passati."
msgstr ""

# The exact sense of this phrase is difficult. At AN 6.37, it says that one gives after rinsing ones own hands. The form here seems to be “Come, Mallika, rinse!” But this seems hard to justify. Comm says it means “give the rinsing water”, which makes sense, but the verb acameti always applies to the act of rinsing, so far as i know. I think the king held his hands over a bowl, and Mallika poured water over them.
#. VAR: ācamehī”ti → ācāmehīti (bj, pts1)
msgctxt "mn87:29.3"
msgid "Ehi, mallike, ācamehī”ti."
msgstr ""

msgctxt "mn87:29.4"
msgid ""
"Atha kho rājā pasenadi kosalo uṭṭhāyāsanā ekaṃsaṃ uttarāsaṅgaṃ karitvā yena "
"bhagavā tenañjaliṃ paṇāmetvā tikkhattuṃ udānaṃ udānesi:"
msgstr ""

#. </p><p>
#. <a class="sc" id="sc17"></a>
msgctxt "mn87:29.5"
msgid "“Namo tassa bhagavato arahato sammāsambuddhassa."
msgstr ""

